  "source": "Corollary:\n. \"Corollary 4.6\"\nof:\n. \"Lemma 4.5 (Pigeonhole Principle)\"\ngiven:\n. E is \\set\n. n is \\set.theoretic.natural.number\nwhere:\n. E \\:equivalent:/ n\nthen:\n. forAll: m is \\set.theoretic.natural.number\n  where:\n  . E \\:equivalent:/ m\n  then:\n  . m = n\nDocumented:\n. description: \"If $E$ is a set and $n \\in \\omega$ with $E \\sim n$, then $n$ is the unique natural number equivalent to $E$. The pigeonhole principle guarantees that distinct natural numbers are never equivalent.\"\nId: \"abd5b742-bb8b-4787-bfb5-9cc96e45c1cf\"",
